\s{If A then B; A, therefore B.}

Most people, even most mathematicians, construct proofs by listing off steps. I
sort of do it differently. I'm a huge fan of a concept called the
\term{Curry-Howard correspondence} (this Curry the same guy from Currying).

Instead of stating your proposition, and listing off steps to prove it, I'm
instead going to 

\begin{enumerate}
  \item Express what I'm trying to prove via types.
  \item Write a function that fits the type of my proof.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{definition}
    The Curry-Howard correspondence states that

    \begin{enumerate}
      \item Types and propositions have identical semantics
      \item Functions and proofs have identical semantics
    \end{enumerate}
\end{definition}

If you have very little math background, that doesn't really seem very
interesting. However, to people who are used to the normal way of proving stuff,
that fact mindblowing.

So, let's say we want to prove that some proposition $a$ implies another
proposition $b$. Well, then, all we have to do is find a function with type

\begin{equation}
    a \implies b
\end{equation}

When dealing with normal non-proofy functions, you can think of the symbol
$\implies$ as saying ``to''. With proofs, it's more helpful to think of the
symbol as ``implies''.

\begin{remark}[Consequence of the Curry-Howard correspondence]
    A value of type $a$, where $a$ is a proposition, is a proof of the
    proposition $a$.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}[Consequence of the Curry-Howard correspondence]
    A function with type $a \implies b$ is a proof that $a$ implies $b$.

    That is, if $a$, then $b$.
\end{remark}

So, how do we disprove something? Well, again, that's not our goal. We instead
want to prove that something isn't provable. That sounds weird, doesn't it?

A staple of logic is called \term{reductio ad absurdum}. It's Latin for
``reduction to the absurd''. Given a proposition $A$, if you can prove that $A$
implies something unprovable, then $A$ is obviously unprovable.

Well, in math, we so happen to have a value that is unprovable. That value is
bottom: $\bot$.

Following along with this logic, if we were to prove that $A$ is unprovable, it
would follow that $A$ implies $\bot$. So, how do we say ``$A$ is unprovable''.

\begin{definition}[Unprovability]
    A proposition $a$ is unprovable if $\lnot a$
\end{definition}

What if you have a proof of both $\lnot A$ and $A$? Well, that's absurd, so
let's call that an instance of reductio ad absurdum.

\begin{definition}[Unprovability by reductio ad absurdum]
    \begin{equation}
        \lnot A = A \implies \bot
    \end{equation}

    That is, proving $\lnot A$ is equivalent to proving that $A \implies \bot$.
\end{definition}

\ss{The big pitfall of propositional logic}

A common mistake is to say ``Well, if $A$ happens, then $B$ will happen. If I
know that $B$ happened, then I can reasonably conclude that $A$ happened at some
point in the past.'' Let's go through an example to show why this doesn't quite
work.

If someone is decapitated, then they are dead, at least within a few seconds.

\begin{equation}
    \label{eq:decapdead}
    \text{Decapitated} \implies \text{Dead}
\end{equation}

